A quicksort algorithm is a sorting algorithm that follows the divide-and-conquer approach. It works by selecting a pivot element from the array and partitioning the other elements into two sub-arrays, according to whether they are less than or greater than the pivot. The sub-arrays are then recursively sorted.

Here is an implementation of the quicksort algorithm in Python, with error handling to handle empty arrays or arrays with a single element:

```python
def quicksort(arr):
    if len(arr) <= 1:
        return arr

    pivot = arr[0]
    less = [x for x in arr[1:] if x <= pivot]
    greater = [x for x in arr[1:] if x > pivot]

    return quicksort(less) + [pivot] + quicksort(greater)
```

